observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. Reorganize the Property Inventory Team which shall conduct the physical inventory of all its property, plant and equipment and prepare and submit the RPCPPE not later than January 31 of the ensuing year, and reconcile property records with accounting ledgers pursuant to the guidelines prescribed in the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume I;
b. Direct the Municipal Accountant to effect the necessary adjustments for the noted errors and omissions, particularly the (i) inclusion of semi-expendable items with net carrying amount of ₱1.344 million; (ii) transfer of completed projects from Trust Fund not reflected in General Fund, with a total cost of ₱18.905 million and accumulated depreciation of ₱4.505 million; and (iii) barangay sub-projects totaling ₱7.273 million still recorded in the books of Municipality instead of the Barangays;
c. Require the MENRO and concerned end-users or recipients of the unrecorded transferred/donated equipment and vehicles to promptly submit to the Municipal Accountant and RSPO the IRP or equivalent Property Transfer Report duly supported with Deed of Donations, MOA and other applicable documents for proper recording in the property cards and books of accounts; and
d. Consider availing the one-time cleansing of accounts prescribed under COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to facilitate the reporting of reliable PPE account balance in the financial statements.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
a. direct the Bids and Awards Committee to submit justification on delayed procurement of breeder stock and other deficiencies, together with the noted lacking documents required for Negotiated Procurement – Two Failed Biddings mode of procurement, in compliance with the RIRR of RA 9184;
b. direct the concerned inspector and end-user of delivered breeder hogs to render justification on signing the IAR despite the noted delayed and incomplete delivery;
c. instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) effect the necessary adjustment in the books of accounts to correct the erroneous recording of procurement of breeder stocks, and (ii) deduct from future claim of supplier the liquidated damages amounting to ₱42,504.00, or demand payment thereof, whichever is applicable, and henceforth, ensure the circumspect review of documents supporting the disbursement vouchers to avoid recurrence of payment of claims with incomplete or inconsistent information/documents; and
d. require the OIC-Municipal Agriculturist and Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain the prescribed property cards and subsidiary ledger for the Biological Assets to be used for monitoring the livestock owned by the Municipality.

We recommended the following courses of action:
a. On work items of the three projects not considered in the COA verified accomplishments costing P2,034,242.21, the Municipal Engineer provide explanation on why the necessary details and technical specifications of such work items discussed above were not reflected in the submitted approved plans and specifications;
b. On defects noted during inspection amounting to P153,718.45, the Municipal Engineer monitor and institute corrective measures on the findings of the COA RO IV-B RTS, or in the alternative, the Municipal Accountant enforce refund of the cost of deficiencies thru deduction from the amount due to respective contractors or demand for payment, as the case may be;
c. On the inclusion of Item 104-Embankment in the detailed estimates of project Local Access Road Upgrading, the Municipal Engineer submit the approved Quality Control Program (QCP) including all the Material Test Reports particularly with regards to soil, for further review and evaluation by the COA RO IV-B RTS; and
d. On variance between contract cost and COA cost estimate of P1,123,474.62, the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer require the concerned contractors to refund the excess amount of contract cost over COA Cost Estimates, as may be deemed warranted.

We recommended that the:
a. Municipal Accountant establish in the books of accounts, if applicable, procured agricultural goods and tools which are awaiting distribution to the beneficiaries of the ICFP Project, ensure that all payments for procured items for distribution are entered in the books of accounts as inventory/supply for distribution, and see to it that all Purchase Requests and Purchase Orders are dated and numbered before entering into contracts and processing payments respectively;
b. Management provide a satisfactory explanation on the selection of an ICFP Coordinator as an ICFP beneficiary;
c. The ICFP Team members and BAC members submit legal bases on the claim of honoraria; and
d. The ICFP Chairman explain the delay in the implementation of project and utilization of fund; and ensure that the ICFP Project serves its true purpose which is to mitigate hunger of the participating poor families.

We recommended that the:
a. BAC Secretariat provide proof of compliance of the posting of the ITB at any conspicuous place in the premises of the Municipality pursuant to Section 21.2.1(a) of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;
b. Municipal Engineer ensure that the Certificate of Acceptance is issued after the lapse of the defects liability period or one year from project completion up to final acceptance of the project pursuant to Section 62.2.2 of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;
c. Municipal Engineer, BAC Chairman, and/or Municipal Accountant submit all the lacking documentary requirements to support the procurement activities for the above projects to avoid suspension in audit; and
d. Municipal Accountant (i) submit the CAF for the projects, and (ii) ensure that all progress billings and final payments are recognized as Construction in Progress pursuant to COA Circular No. 2015-009. Progress.

We recommended that the:
a. BAC Secretariat provide proof of compliance of the posting of the ITB at any conspicuous place in the premises of the Municipality pursuant to Section 21.2.1(a) of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;
b. Municipal Engineer ensure that the Certificate of Acceptance is issued after the lapse of the defects liability period or one year from project completion up to final acceptance of the project pursuant to Section 62.2.2 of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;
c. Municipal Engineer, BAC Chairman submit all the lacking documentary requirements to support the procurement activities for the above projects to avoid suspension in audit; and
d. Municipal Accountant submit the CAF for the projects, and ensure that all progress billings and final payments are recognized as Construction in Progress pursuant to COA Circular No. 2015-009.

We recommended that the Honorable Mayor enjoin the department heads to assist the Municipal Accountant in the implementation of the accounting system and the new chart of accounts in compliance with the requirement of COA Circular No. 2016-004 dated September 30, 2016, as follows:
a. The Municipal Treasurer provide copies of memorandum of agreements, service contracts and other agreements with respect to deposits of funds and other contracts which affect the accounting of financial assets and liabilities and the management of physical assets of the local government unit;
b. Municipal Budget Officer provide the updated Registries of Appropriation, Allotment and Obligations, and furnish copies of the approved budget, supplemental budgets, realignment and distribution of the lump sum appropriation and the corresponding legislative approval;
c. Municipal Engineer provide report on the cost and status of ongoing projects and submit detailed cost of components of infrastructure projects; and
d. Further, the Municipal Accountant: (i) reclassify the cost of the materials and labor for the installation of solar street lights under Power Supply System to Repair and Maintenance – Infrastructure Assets (Power System) in accordance with COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015; and (ii) analyze the Registry of Public Infrastructure to comply with Item 3.7 of COA Circular No. 2016-004 dated September 30, 2016 on the recognition of the 25% target implementation of the Public Infrastructures in the books of accounts.

